<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The third growth of leaves on the vandalized Treaty Oak in Austin, Tex., is 
turning "brown and crunchy," but a city forester said he remains hopeful the 
landmark tree will refoliate -- at least partially -- next spring. But forester 
John Giedraitis said even if the 500-year-old tree survives, it will not be the 
same sprawling live oak that admirers remember before it was intentionally 
poisoned with the powerful herbicide Velpar. City workers have removed all the 
poisoned soil and are continuing to mist the tree with cooling spring water and 
protect it with giant sun shades to lessen stress as temperatures climb into 
the high 90s each day. Paul Stedman Cullen, 45, of Elroy has been charged with 
felony criminal mischief in the poisoning of the tree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
