<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALMANAC: COMPARING HOME PRICES; 
</P>
<P>
SWEET O.C. MEMORY: A HOUSE FOR $34,000 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Remember those ancient times when you could buy a house in Orange County for 
$34,000? Not so ancient, actually. How about 1974? 
</P>
<P>
Selected houses in the county were appraised that year as part of a survey by 
the Real Estate Research Council of Southern California, and the average price 
of the houses appraised was $34,000. 
</P>
<P>
The council conducts appraisals every six months -- on the same houses, 
whenever possible -- and its Orange County average for April of this year was 
$232,900. 
</P>
<P>
Prices have risen even faster in Los Angeles County. In 1974, the $40,600 
average in L.A. County was 18% higher than the Orange County average. By this 
year, the gap had widened to 34%. 
</P>
<P>
The comparison with San Diego County is more favorable. Houses appraised there 
had a higher average price than the Orange County average as recently as 1986, 
but now the Orange County houses have an edge of 12%. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
HOME PRICE INDEX 
</P>
<P>
A measure of home-price appreciation is the Home Price Index compiled twice a 
year by the Real Estate Research Council of Southern California. The council 
sponsors appraisals of selected homes twice a year -- using the same homes 
whenever possible. The index uses 1975 as a base year with a number of 100. The 
most recent index figure for Orange County, 490, indicates that the average 
price of appraised homes has increased nearly fivefold since 1975. 
</P>
