<HEADLINE>
<P>
PANEL VOTES TO ABOLISH S&amp;L INSURING AGENCIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Wire and Staff Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A House-Senate conference committee Tuesday voted to abolish the U.S. agencies 
that regulate and insure accounts at federal savings and loan associations and 
transfer their operations to other agencies. 
</P>
<P>
The action came on the opening day of a conference to resolve differences 
between House and Senate bills to bail out the thrift industry by closing or 
merging failing associations. 
</P>
<P>
The bills would authorize a $50-billion federal bond issue to close hundreds of 
S&amp;Ls, tighten financial rules for thrifts and increase penalties for bank 
fraud. The Senate bill passed in April; the House legislation was approved in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
Most functions of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board and its Federal Savings and 
Loan Insurance Corp. would be transferred to the Federal Deposit Insurance 
Corp., the bank insurer that has taken over operations of many failing thrifts. 
</P>
<P>
The bill would also create a Resolution Trust Corp. to manage and resolve 
failed S&amp;Ls and establish an office of thrift supervision in the Treasury 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
Late Tuesday, the conferees also voted to establish a regional office in Dallas 
to investigate S&amp;L fraud in the Southwest. The House bill originally called 
for such offices in both Dallas and Los Angeles, while the Senate version 
provided for none. The compromise cut out the proposed Los Angeles office. 
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Thomas Foley urged members to work quickly so that Congress could 
pass the bill before its summer recess begins Aug. 4. 
</P>
<P>
A key issue that the conference must decide is whether the total cost of the 
bill, estimated at $157 billion by the Bush Administration and much higher by 
other economists, will be included in the federal budget. 
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady wants the plan off-budget and has hinted that 
he might recommend that Bush veto the bill if the cost is on-budget. The House 
voted to put the costs in the budget, but the Senate kept the costs off the 
budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
