<HEADLINE>
<P>
UNVEIL 'SYMBOL OF HOPE'; 
</P>
<P>
FUGITIVE CHINESE STUDENT LEADERS APPEAR IN PARIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two fugitive leaders of China's pro-democracy movement appeared in public today 
for the first time since the uprising was crushed by troops in Beijing last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
Wuerkaixi and Li Lu, wanted by China for inciting rebellion, emerged under 
heavy guard at a ceremony to unveil a replica of the Goddess of Democracy 
statue erected in the Chinese capital's Tien An Men Square during mass 
demonstrations.As the two appeared at a Paris science center, surrounded by a 
group of 10 plainclothes bodyguards, a crowd of about 50 people gasped in 
surprise and cheered loudly. 
</P>
<P>
Li, who said he helped build the original goddess torn down on June 4 by 
Chinese troops, said: "The statue is a symbol of hope for Chinese people. Now 
that I have seen it again, it is like seeing more hope for China." 
</P>
<P>
Beijing has protested to France about harboring the dissidents, saying they are 
plotting to overthrow the Chinese government. 
</P>
<P>
French Culture Minister Jack Lang arrived earlier than the students at the 
unveiling. His appearance with the dissidents was likely to infuriate Chinese 
authorities further. 
</P>
<P>
The French government has supported the Chinese students who built the statue 
reminiscent of a major French gift to the United States, the Statue of Liberty. 
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Communist Party leader Jiang Zemin today told Chinese officials 
they must work harder to counter Western "rumors" about the crackdown on 
pro-democracy protesters last month and Premier Li Peng promised that Chinese 
students abroad who participated in protest rallies will be welcomed back to 
China and not punished. 
</P>
<P>
Jiang and Li were speaking at the end of a six-day conference of 151 
ambassadors and other diplomats who were called back to Beijing to discuss 
Chinese foreign policy in the wake of political turmoil at home. 
</P>
<P>
Many Western nations are allowing Chinese students to extend their stays 
because of fears they face persecution if they return to China. More than 2,000 
people have been reported arrested for joining protests. 
</P>
<P>
"Because they were far from the motherland and influenced by the Western media, 
they didn't understand the true situation and participated in protests and said 
some extremist words," Premier Li was quoted as saying about students living 
abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
