BLACK PROBLEMS ARE AMERICA'S -- QUAYLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
High infant mortality and dropout rates among blacks are problems all America 
must work to overcome, Vice President Dan Quayle told the NAACP convention 
today. 
</P>
<P>
Quayle spoke on the fourth day of the National Assn. for the Advancement of 
Colored People's annual convention in Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
"If President George Bush were in the country, you know he would be speaking to 
you," Quayle said. Bush is in Hungary today as part of his tour of Eastern 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
Quayle, who received a good reception from the NAACP's leadership, said the 
Bush Administration is committed to promoting civil rights and the President 
has met several times with civil rights leaders. 
</P>
<P>
He reviewed the history of the civil rights movement, and said, "Today, there 
is less bigotry than before, but there is still bigotry -- and bigots." 
</P>
<P>
Quayle cited statistics indicating the social and economic disadvantage of 
blacks. 
</P>
<P>
"Let us not forget that the black infant mortality rate is twice as high as for 
whites," said Quayle, who also spoke of the disproportionately high dropout 
rate among young blacks. 
</P>
<P>
"These are not just black problems, these are America's problems," Quayle said. 
</P>
